\begin{document}
\begin{nparagraph}
What I am going to go into next is -- or should be -- obvious, but there is an important
point I want to make.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}[label=slide-attendance]
\frametitle{Do I need to attend the lectures}
\begin{itemize}
\item<1-> Attendance is not mandatory for the \useSGvar{courseacronym} lecture
\item<2-> There are two ways of learning \useSGvar{courseacronym}:\lec{both are OK, your mileage may vary}
\begin{itemize}
\item Approach \blue{B}: Read a \blue{Book}
\ifSGvar{courseacronym}{AI}{\cite{RusNor:AIMA09} or follow~\cite{NorTru:itai}}
\item Approach \blue{I}: come to the lectures, be \blue{involved}, interrupt me whenever you have a question.
\end{itemize}
The only advantage of \blue{I} over \blue{B} is that books do not answer questions
\lec{yet! \ogre we are working on this in AI research}
\item<3-> Approach \blue{S}: come to the lectures and \blue{sleep} \red{does not work}!
\item<4->
\begin{sparagraph}[title=I really mean it]
If you come to class, be involved, ask questions, challenge me with comments, tell
me about errors, \ldots
\begin{itemize}
\item<5-> I would much rather have a lively discussion than get through all the
slides
\item<6-> You learn more, I have more fun \lec{Approach \blue{B} serves as a backup}
\item<7-> You may have to change your habits, overcome shyness, \ldots\lec{please do!}
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\item<8-> This is what I get paid for, and I am more expensive than most books\lec{get
your money's worth}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\end{document}

