\begin{document}
\begin{smodule}{cs-culture}
\begin{nparagraph}
One of the most important tasks in an inter/trans-disciplinary enterprise -- and that
what ``digital humanities'' is, fundamentally -- is to understand the disciplinary
language, intuitions and foundational assumptions of the respective other side. Assuming
that most students are more versed in the ``humanities and social sciences'' side we
want to try to give an overview of the ``\sr{computer-science?CS}{computer science}
culture''.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Academic Culture in Computer Science}
\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{sdefinition}
The \definame{academic culture} is the overall style of working, research, and
discussion in an academic field.
\end{sdefinition}
\item
\begin{sassertion}[style=observation]
There are significant differences in the \sn{academic culture} between
\sr{computer-science?CS}{computer science}, the humanities and the social
sciences.
\end{sassertion}
\item \sr{computer-science?CS}{Computer science} is an \red{engineering
discipline}\lec{we build things}
\begin{itemize}
\item given a problem we look for a (mathematical) model, we can think with
\item once we have one, we try to re-express it with fewer ``primitives'' (concepts)
\item once we have, we generalize it \lec{make it more widely applicable}
\item only then do we \sn{implement} it in a program\lec{ideally}
\end{itemize}
Design of versatile, usable, and elegant tools is an important concern
\item Almost all technical literature is in English.\lec{technical vocabulary too}
\item \sr{computer-science?computer scientist}{CSlings} love shallow
hierarchies.\lec{no personality cult; alle per Du}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{nparagraph}
Please keep in mind that -- self-awareness is always difficult -- the list below may be
incomplete and clouded by mirror-gazing.
\end{nparagraph}
\end{smodule}
\end{document}

