\begin{document}
\begin{smodule}{IWGS-grading}
\begin{nparagraph}
Now we come to a topic that is always interesting to the students: the grading scheme:
The short story is that things are complicated. We have to strike a good balance between
what is didactically useful and what is allowed by Bavarian law and the FAU rules.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Assessment, Grades}
\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Grading Background/Theory]
Only modules are graded! \lec{by the law}
\begin{itemize}
\item Module ``DH-Einführung'' (DHE) \hateq courses IWGS1/2, DH-Einführung.
\item DHE module grade \ergo pass/fail determined by ``portfolio'' \hateq collection
of contributions/assessments.
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Assessment Practice]
The IWGS assessments in the ``portfolio'' consist of
\begin{itemize}
\item weekly homework assignments,\lec{practice IWGS concepts and tools}
\item 60 minutes exam directly after lectures end: \useSGvar{examdate}.
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Retake Exam]
60 min exam at the end of the exam break.\lec{\useSGvar{retakedate}}
\end{sparagraph}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{nparagraph}
Homework assignments, %quizzes,
and end-semester exam may seem like a lot of work -- and indeed
they are -- but you will need practice (getting your hands dirty) to master the
concepts. We will go into the details next.
\end{nparagraph}
\end{smodule}
\end{document}

Archive: courses/FAU/IWGS/course
Filepath: course/slides/homeworks.en

\begin{document}
\begin{frame}
\usemodule[smglom/arithmetics]{mod?percentage}
\frametitle{\useSGvar{courseacronym} Homework Assignments}
\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Homeworks]
will be small individual problem/programming/system assignments
\begin{itemize}
\item but take time to solve\lec{at least read them directly \ergo questions}
\item group submission if and only if explicitly permitted.
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[style=warning]
Without trying the homework assignments you are unlikely to pass the exam.
\end{sparagraph}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Admin]
To keep things running smoothly
\begin{itemize}
\item Homeworks will be posted on \href{https://www.studon.fau.de/studon}{StudOn}.
\item Sign up for \useSGvar{courseacronym} under \useSGvar{studon}.
\item Homeworks are handed in electronically there. \lec{plain text, program files, PDF}
\item \red{Go to the tutorials, discuss with your TA}!\lec{they are there for you!}
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Homework Discipline]
\begin{itemize}
\item \red{Start early}!\lec{many assignments need more than one evening's work}
\item Don't start by sitting at a blank screen \lec{talking \& study group help}
\item Humans will be trying to understand the text/code/math when grading it.
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{nparagraph}
It is very well-established experience that without doing the homework assignments (or
something similar) on your own, you will not master the concepts, you will not even be
able to ask sensible questions, and take nothing home from the course. Just sitting in
the course and nodding is not enough!
\end{nparagraph}
\end{document}

