\begin{document}
\begin{smodule}{css-boxmodel}

\begin{nparagraph}
We now come to one of the most important conceptual parts of \sn{CSS?CSS}: the \sr{CSS box model}{box
model}. Understanding it is essential for dealing with \sn{CSS?CSS} based layouts.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{The \sr{CSS box model}{CSS Box Model}}
\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{sdefinition}
For layout, \sn{CSS?CSS} considers all \sn{html?HTML} \sr{XML element}{elements} as
\definame[post=es]{box}, i.e. document areas with a given \definame{width} and
\definame{height}. A \sn{CSS?CSS} \sn{box} has four parts:
\begin{itemize}
\item \definame{content}: the content of the \sn{box}, where text and \sr{digital
image}{images} appear.
\item \definame{padding}: clears an area around the \sn{content}. The \sn{padding}
is transparent.
\item \definame{border} a border that goes around the \sn{padding} and \sn{content}.
\item \definame{margin} clears an area outside the \sn{border}. The \sn{margin} is
transparent.
\end{itemize}
The latter three wrap around the \sn{content} and add to its size.
\end{sdefinition}
\item All parts of a \sn{box} can be customized with suitable \sn{CSS?CSS}
\sr{CSS?property}{properties}:
\begin{center}
\parbox[c]{5cm}{\lstinputmhlisting[linerange=4-10,linewidth=5cm]{digdocs/code/css-boxmodel.html}}
\qquad\parbox[c]{4cm}{\mhgraphics[width=5cm]{digdocs/PIC/css-boxmodel}}
\end{center}
Note that the overall \sn{width} of the \sn{CSS?CSS} \sn{box} is
$\natplus{300,\nattimes[cdot]{2,3,25}} = 450$ pixels.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{nparagraph}
As a summary of the above, we can visualize the \sn{CSS box model} in a
diagram:
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{The \sr{CSS box model}{CSS Box Model}: Diagram}
\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{sdefinition}
The following diagram summarizes the \definame{CSS box model}
\cmhtikzinput{digdocs/tikz/css-boxmodel}
\end{sdefinition}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\end{smodule}
\end{document}

