\begin{document}
\begin{smodule}{jupyterLab}

\begin{nparagraph}
In \useSGvar{courseacronym}, we want to use the \sn{jupyterLab} cloud service. This runs
the \python \sn{interpreter?interpreter} on a cloud server and gives you a
\sr{webbrowser?web browser}{browser} \sn{window} with a \sn{web IDE}, which you can use
for \sn[post=ing]{interact} with the \sn{interpreter?interpreter}. You will have to make
an account there; details to follow.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{\sn{jupyterLab} A Cloud IDE for \python}
\begin{itemize}
\item<1->
\begin{sparagraph}[style=start,title=For helping you]
it would be good if the TAs could access to your code
\end{sparagraph}
\item<1->
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Idea]
Use a \inlinedef[for=jupyterLab]{\definame{web-IDE?web IDE} (a web based integrated
development environment): \sn{jupyterLab}}, which you can use for
\sn[post=ing]{interact} with the \sn{interpreter?interpreter}.
\end{sparagraph}
\item<2-> We will use \sn{jupyterLab} for \useSGvar{courseacronym}.\lec{but you can also
use \python locally}
\item<2->
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Homework]
Set up \sn{jupyterLab}
\begin{itemize}
\item make an account at \url{http://jupyter.kwarc.info}
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{nparagraph}
The advantage of a cloud IDE like \sn{jupyterLab} for a course like
\useSGvar{courseacronym} is that you do not need any \sn[post=ation]{install},
cannot lose your files, and your teachers (the course instructor and the teaching
assistants) can see (and even directly \sn{interact} with) the your run time
environment. This gives us a much more controlled setting and we can help you better.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{nparagraph}
Both $\idlethree$ as well as \sn{jupyterLab} come with an integrated editor for writing
\python programs. These editors gives you \python syntax
highlighting, and \sn{interpreter?interpreter} and debugger integration. In
short, $\idlethree$ and \sn{jupyterLab} are integrated development environments for
\python. Let us now go through the interface of the \sn{jupyterLab} IDE.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{\sn{jupyterLab} Components}
\begin{itemize}
\item<1->
\begin{sdefinition}
The \sn{jupyterLab} \definame{dashboard?dashboard} gives you access to all
components.
\only<1>{\cmhgraphics[width=8.5cm]{progintro/PIC/jupyterLab}}
\end{sdefinition}
\item<2->
\begin{sdefinition}
The \sn{jupyterLab} \definame{python console}, i.e. a \python
\sn{interpreter?interpreter} in your
\sr{webbrowser?web browser}{browser}.\lec{use this for \python
\sn[post=ion]{interact} and testing.}
\only<2>{\cmhgraphics[width=11cm]{progintro/PIC/jupyterLab-python-console}}
\end{sdefinition}
\item<3->
\begin{sdefinition}
The \sn{jupyterLab} \definame{jupyterLab?terminal}, i.e.

a $\unixOS$
\sn{shell?shell} in your browser.\lec{use this for managing files}
\only<3>{\cmhgraphics[width=11cm]{progintro/PIC/jupyterLab-bash-console}}
\end{sdefinition}
\item<4->
File: [smglom/computing]{mod/shell.en}

\item<4->
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Useful \sn{shell} \sr{instruction}{commands}]
See e.g.~\cite{Allen:nutbsc18} for a basic tutorial
\begin{itemize}
\item \lstinline|ls|: ``list'' the \sns{file} in this \sn{directory}
\item \lstinline|mkdir|: ``make'' \sr{directory}{folder} (called
``\sn{directory}'')
\item \lstinline|pwd|: ``print \sn{working directory}''\lec{where am I}
\item \lstinline|cd| $\pmetavar{dirname}$: ``change \sn{directory}''
\begin{itemize}
\item if $\pmetavar{dirname} = \lstinline|..|$: one up in the \sn{directory}
\sn{tree}
\item empty \pmetavar{dirname}: go to your \sn{home directory}.
\end{itemize}
\item \lstinline|rm| $\pmetavar{name}$:  remove \sn{file}/\sn{directory}
\item \lstinline|cp|/\lstinline|mv| $\pmetavar{filename}$ $\pmetavar{newname}$: copy
to or rename
\item \lstinline|cp|/\lstinline|mv| $\pmetavar{filename}$ $\pmetavar{dirname}$: copy
or move to
\item \ldots see \cite{Allen:nutbsc18} for more \ldots
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\end{smodule}
\end{document}

