\begin{document}
\begin{smodule}{jupyterNotebooks}

\begin{nparagraph}
We now come to the signature component of \sn{jupyterLab}: \sns{jupyter notebook}. They
take the important practice of documenting \sn{computer-code?code} to a whole new
level. Instead of just allowing \sns{commenting?comment} in \sn{program} \sns{file},
they provide rich text cells, in which we can write elaborate text.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}[label=slide.jupyterNotebooks]
\frametitle{Jupyter Notebooks}
\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{sdefinition}
\Definame[post=s]{jupyter notebook} are documents that combine live runnable code
with rich, narrative text (for comments and explanations).
\end{sdefinition}
\item
\begin{sdefinition}
\Sns{jupyter notebook} consist of \definame[post=s]{cell} which come in three forms:
\begin{itemize}
\item a \definame{raw cell} shows text as is,
\item a \definame{markdown cell} interprets the contents as markdown text,\lec{later more}
\item a \definame{code cell} interprets the contents as (e.g.  \python) code.
\end{itemize}
