\begin{document}
\begin{smodule}{webapp-anatomy}

\begin{nparagraph}
We have seen that \sns{web application} are a common way of building
\sn{appsys-software?application software}. To understand how this works let us now
have a look at the components.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}[label=slide.webapp-anatomy]
\frametitle{Anatomy of a Web Application}
\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{sdefinition}
A \sn{web application} consists of two parts:
\begin{itemize}
\item A \definame{front end} that handles the \sr{interact}{user interaction}.
\item A \definame{back end} that stores, computes and serves the application content.
\end{itemize}
\cmhtikzinput{webapps/tikz/webapp-anatomy}
Both parts rely on (separate) computational facilities.\\
A \sn{database?database} as a \definame{persistence layer} is optional.
\end{sdefinition}
\item
\begin{sparagraph}[title=Note]
The \sn{webbrowser?web browser}, \sn{webserver?web server}, and
\sn{database?database} can
\begin{itemize}
\item be deployed on different \sns{computer}, \lec{high throughput}
\item all run on your laptop \lec{e.g. for development}
\end{itemize}
\end{sparagraph}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
\end{smodule}
\end{document}

