Archive: courses/Jacobs/GenCS/course
Filepath: www/snip/addressing-intro.en

\begin{document}
\begin{sparagraph}
\usemodule{www/slides?www-concepts}
The essential idea is that the \sr{WWW}{World Wide Web} consists of a set of resources
(documents, \sr{digital image}{images}, movies, etc.) that are connected by links (like
a spider-web). In the \sn{WWW}, the links consist of pointers to addresses of
resources. To realize them, we only need addresses of resources (much as we have IP
numbers as addresses to hosts on the \sn{internet}).
\end{sparagraph}
\end{document}

Archive: courses/Jacobs/GenCS/course
Filepath: www/snip/clientside-interaction.en

\begin{document}
\begin{sparagraph}
\usemodule[smglom/math]{mod?mathematics}
\usemodule{www/slides?www-concepts}
\usemodule[smglom/computing]{mod?interpreter}
One of the main advantages of moving documents from their traditional ink-on-paper form
into an electronic form is that we can \sn{interact} with them more directly. But there
are many more \sn[post=ions]{interact} than just browsing \sns{hyperlink} we can think
of: adding margin notes, looking up definitions or translations of particular words, or
copy-and-pasting \sn{mathematical} formulae into a computer algebra system. All of them
(and many more) can be made, if we make documents programmable. For that we need three
ingredients:
\begin{enumerate}[\em i)]
\item a machine-accessible representation of the document structure, and
\item a program \sn{interpreter} in the \sn{web browser}, and
\item a way to send \sns{program} to the \sr{web browser}{browser}
together with the document.
\end{enumerate}
We will sketch the \sn{WWW} solution to this in the following.
\end{sparagraph}
\end{document}

