\begin{document}
\begin{smodule}{natural-numbers}

\begin{nparagraph}
The first system for \sn{number} representations is very simple; so simple in fact that
it has been discovered and used a long time ago.
\end{nparagraph}

\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Natural Numbers}
\begin{itemize}
\item \Sns{number} are symbolic representations of numeric
\sr{quantity}{quantities}.
\item There are many ways to represent \sns{number}\lec{more on this later}
\item Let's take the simplest one\lec{about 8,000 to 10,000 years old}
\begin{center}
\end{center}
\item We count by making marks on some surface.
\item For instance $\sslash{\sslash{\sslash{\sslash\szero}}}$ stands for the
\sn{number} four\lec{be it in 4 apples, or 4 worms}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{nparagraph}
\usemodule[smglom/epistemology]{mod?meaning}
In addition to manipulating normal objects directly linked to their daily survival,
humans also invented the manipulation of place-holders or symbols. A \emph{symbol}
represents an object or a set of objects in an abstract way. The earliest examples for
symbols are the cave paintings showing iconic silhouettes of animals like the famous
ones of Cro-Magnon.  The invention of symbols is not only an artistic, pleasurable
``waste of time'' for humans, but it had tremendous consequences. There is
archaeological evidence that in ancient times, namely at least some 8000 to 10000 years
ago, humans started to use tally bones for counting. This means that the symbol ``bone
with marks'' was used to represent numbers. The important aspect is that this bone is a
symbol that is completely detached from its original down to earth \sn{meaning}, most
likely of being a tool or a waste product from a meal. Instead it stands for a universal
concept that can be applied to arbitrary objects.
\end{nparagraph}
\end{smodule}
\end{document}

